text.tspan: Curate
a Cure
Day without Art is an event that takes place on December
first every year to recognize AIDs. This event started in
1989 on the day the Worlds health organization dubbed
as World AIDs day in order to raise awareness. The AIDS
crisis had been worsening over the years and the Visual
AIDS organization had assembled Day without Art as a
response. Artists, writers, curators and others in the
creative field were called upon to participate in this event.
The goal was to raise awareness, give more information
on the disease, safe sex, and help find a cure. They also
wanted the event to honor those who lost their lives to
AIDS/HIV or who were diagnosed with it.
Many responded and participated in this event. Many
museums, art galleries, and others had covered art
works and dimmed the lighting in honor of the lost
lives. In place of the art work information on AIDS and
safer sex were displayed. In addition to that, creators
put on performances, readings, memorials and other
things in ways of showing and honoring the lost lives
and bringing attention to deviststing disease. Over the
years, this event has grown and taken on many
different forms, but at the base it is still about bringing
focus to a horrible thing and honoring those who died.
